Subject: Harlem Renaissance Party
Description:
In celebration of Black History Month, the Office of Diversity and Inclusion will present a Harlem Renaissance Party in the Student Lounge for all Campus. We invite faculty, staff and students to join us for a great night.

Music provided by: Marlin McKay Band

The Harlem Renaissance was the development of the Harlem neighborhood in New York City as a Black cultural mecca in the early 20th Century and the subsequent social and artistic explosion that resulted. Lasting roughly from the 1910s through the mid-1930s, the period is considered a golden age in African American culture, manifesting in literature, music, stage performance and art. Subject: Belle of the Blue & Beaus Too Scholarship Pageant
Collier Lecture - The Intersection of Story and Science
Description:
Ashley Clayton is a GC alum who earned her undergraduate degree in psychology and her master's in community psychology. She is the recipient of GC's first Young Alumni Award. She has worked as a research program assistant and director at Yale Medical School since graduating with her master's. She is also a prolific publisher of research and a published author and poet.

Ashley's presentation will focus on the intersection of story with science. She'll be discussing mental health and community based participatory research, including sharing her personal story of mental illness, her research, and what it's like to be a researcher in the field. She'll also challenge the audience to think about our subjectivity/objectivity, who we consider to be "experts", and how her work relates
to justice. Contact: Karyn McKenzie

Subject: Women's History Month Celebration/Speaker
Description:
In celebration of Women's History Month, we will host Ms. Passion Richardson on our campus. 

Passion is an American former track and field athlete who competed in sprinting events. She had most of her success with the American women's 4×100 m relay team. She ran in the heats at the 2000 Summer Olympics and the Americans won the bronze medal in the final. After graduating in 1993 she went on to study marketing at the University of Kentucky. While there she competed athletically for the Kentucky Wildcats and gained four All-American honours: she was an indoor 55 metres finalist in 1994 and 1996, a 4×100 metres relay finalist in 1996, and a 100 metres finalist in 1997.

October 6 is Spanish Cinema Day, a day in which Spanish cinema is celebrated  worldwide. This year, the film Las niñas (2020) will be featured. The Filmoteca Española, an official institution of the Ministry of Culture of Spain, provides the film.
